results.title: Man in the desert
results.creator_credit: Edwin Moses, Keith Gow, David Bairstow and Australian Commonwealth Film Unit
results.brief_description:
Episode of Series “Australian Geography”.
Looks at the human geography of our arid zones by examining the lives of First Nations people, cattlemen and miners - men who live in the waste-land of Australia’s deserts. Almost 90% of arid lands are used by someone at some time for some purpose. Questions why man is attracted to the desert. Explains how man has adapted to this environment and what effect this has had on the environment.

results.title: Emulation of Carriers at War 1941-1945: Fleet Carrier Operations in the Pacific for DOS
results.brief_description:
Carriers at War 1941-1945: Fleet Carrier Operations in the Pacific is a war simulation game. In the game, the player takes on the role of the task force commander in the Pacific Theater during World War II. The player can play as both the U.S. and the Japanese Empire in scenarios such as Pearl Harbor, Coral Sea, Midway, Eastern Solomons, Santa Cruz and Philippine Sea. The game is played on a 72x84 hexagonal grid on which different units and squadrons, such as naval vessels and land based aircraft, are positioned. The player chooses actions for these units, the consequences for which are simulated by the computer. The game is quasi real-time, meaning that the game can be paused at any given moment at which time the player can give orders to the units. All interaction with the game is through a menu interface. Orders that can be given to units include strike, escort, transport, support, refuel and more complex maneuvers such as strike routines.

Source: Play It Again website:
http://www.ourdigitalheritage.org/archive/playitagain/games/goldfields/

The game is played on a 72x84 hexagonal grid on which different units and squadrons, such as naval vessels and land based aircraft, are positioned. The player chooses actions for these units, the consequences for which are simulated by the computer. The game is quasi real-time, meaning that the game can be paused at any given moment at which time the player can give orders to the units. All interaction with the game is through a menu interface. Orders that can be given to units include strike, escort, transport, support, refuel and more complex maneuvers such as strike routines.

results.title: Emulation of Ladder Invaders II for Commodore 64
results.brief_description:
Ladder Invaders II is a single player arcade game, The player is the middle purple figure and can move up using “S” and down using “X” on a horizontal ladder. Two ladders on the left and right of the player have green figures scaling up. The player must fire on them using “RETURN” to prevent them from reaching the top of their ladder. The laser the player fires goes both left and right and hits all ladders. Once 3 green figures reaches the top, the player loses. The laser also removes the orange background but has not noticable effect on gameplay.

Original game created for Commodore 64 by Matthew Hall and released into the public domain circa 1985. More info on Matt Hall’s games can be found at: http://www.ourdigitalheritage.org/archive/playitagain/bedroom-coders-matthew-hall-15-commodore-64-games-rescued-from-decaying-cassettes/

results.title: Emulation of Sherlock for Commodore 64
results.brief_description:
In this text and graphics adventure mystery game you are the world’s greatest sleuth - Sherlock Holmes. Teamed up with Doctor Watson and dealing with the inept Inspector Lestrade, you must solve a double murder in Leatherhead. As well as studying the clues, you must interrogate NPCs, who will react differently if they know certain information. Time is important to the game - you have a limited amount, and must make use of trains which come at varying times. Unusually, the descriptive text given by the game is kept separate from entered commands, which are stored at the bottom of the screen.

Original game developed by Melbourne House. Published in 1984 by Melbourne House.
